It's difficult to remember sometimes, but the # of pieces I have pointing at a4 out numbers yours so the pawn will just get lost in the exchange, and then your b pawn will closely follow.  with those two passed pawns, I think Ra6 was in order before pushing this pawn, that way you could get your king's rook over to a8 and you would have had some real power on the queens side of my board.

sorry about this one.  I know you were running out of squares and I'm not entirely sure much at all could be done, but trading a rook and a pawn for a pawn and a knight when you are that far behind in material is never a good idea.  I will stop here.  I am going to go back and look at the opening again.  I think there was a move in there that would have helped you in the center more.  Certainly Nf6 was one of them.  I annotated this game to help my friend adui out, or try anyway, not to impress any chess geniuses.  I hope this will help some, adui.
